{"id": 223691810, "title": "Face of Senior Cat Who Was 'Loved for 14 Years' Before Ending Up in Shelter", "text": "Everybody wants to adopt a kitten, but when it comes to older cats their chances become smaller every year that passes, especially when they have health conditions. That's why many of them end up living in a shelter for the remainder of their lives.A viral TikTok video shared earlier this month by P.A.W.S. of Tinley Park, an animal shelter in Illinois, under the username @p.a.w.s._of_tinley_park, shows a 17-year-old cat named Daisy looking for a family after losing hers not once, but twice.The post explains that Daisy was homed and \"loved for 14 years,\" but when her family moved away they gave her to someone new. Unfortunately, that person recently fell ill and now Daisy is a senior homeless cat, looking for a new loving family.\"Meet out Sweet Senior Daisy, a 17 1/2 year old declawed girl. She is calm, sweet, and loving. Daisy has kidney disease and requires a prescription diet,\" the video's caption reads.Newsweek has reached out to @p.a.w.s._of_tinley_park for comment via a website contact form. We could not verify the details of the case.Chronic kidney disease (CKD) is a common problem in aging cats and while there's currently no cure for it, a veterinarian can help you find ways to manage it.Symptoms that your cat may have kidney disease include: drinking more, peeing more, eating less, losing weight, and vomiting. Other symptoms include lethargy, bad breath, mouth ulcers, sudden blindness, and a messy coat.Each year, 6.3 million pets enter U.S. shelters, which is an average of 17,260 a day, according to the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. The number of dogs and cats taken in by pet shelters hit 46,807 during January 2023, an increase of 1,744 compared with January 2022, the 24Pet 'Shelter Watch Report' found.Around 920,000 surrendered animals are euthanized every year. Shelters are striving to minimize euthanasia rates by promoting adoption campaigns, spaying and neutering programs, and behavior rehabilitation.TikTok Users ReactThe video quickly went viral on TikTok and has so far received over 368,100 views and 55,300 likes on the platform.One user, Amanda, wrote: \"I don't understand this...if I move my pets come with me period.\"Melissa Brewerton added: \"My boy just turned 17 back in March. I can't even imagine him having to spend his last days in a shelter. Someone please give this sweet girl a home for however long she has!\"Christina commented: \"Daisy deserves a comfortable home, a loving human that will be there for her in the end. Please.\"Do you have funny and adorable videos or pictures of your pet you want to share? Send them to life@newsweek.com with some details about your best friend and they could appear in our Pet of the Week lineup.", "summary": "Daisy lost her family not once, but twice before ending up in a shelter. Now that she's 17 years old with kidney disease, she's in desperate need of a home.", "url": "https://www.newsweek.com/face-senior-cat-who-was-loved-14-years-before-ending-shelter-1904401", "image": "https://d.newsweek.com/en/full/2398726/cat-shelter-after-14-years.png", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-05-26 13:00:02", "author": "Maria Azzurra Volpe", "authors": ["Maria Azzurra Volpe"], "language": "en", "source_country": "us", "sentiment": -0.089}